WELLINGTON, Aug 14 (Reuters) - Following are some of the lead stories from New Zealand metropolitan newspapers on Thursday.

Stories may be taken from either the paper or Internet editions of the papers. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.  DOMINION POST(www.stuff.co.nz) Chinese rail workers 'exploited': Chinese workers hired to repair KiwiRail's asbestos-riddled locomotives are being paid as little as $3 an hour, Labour MP Trevor Mallard has claimed. - - - - Nicky Hager reveals Whale Oil links to Nats: Thousands of leaked emails have revealed the extent of the relationship between Right-wing blogger Cameron Slater and prominent National Party figures. - - - - Te Mihi geothermal station to boost Contact: Contact Energy <CEN.NZ> will today officially open its new NZ$623 million Te Mihi geothermal power station, near Taupo's long-established Wairakei power station. - - - - Mowbray boss laments lack of growth: Mowbray Collectables' <MOW.NZ> outgoing chief executive John Mowbray has apologised to shareholders for not growing the company significantly in the 14 years since it listed on the NZX. - - - -   NEW ZEALAND HERALD (www.nzherald.co.nz) Book alleges dirty National Party politics; PM's office says claims 'unfounded': John Key has come under attack in a book that paints his administration as being obsessed with "dirty politics". - - - - ASB profit hits NZ$806m high: An improving economy helped boost ASB's <CBA.AX> annual net profit by 14 per cent to a record NZ$806 million, but the bank's chief executive, Barbara Chapman, says bad-debt expenses are likely to begin trending upwards from their present low levels. - - - - Precinct's NZ$500m plan for tower: The NZ$1.7 billion landlord Precinct Properties <PCT.NZ> will spend up to NZ$500 million building its new Downtown tower near Auckland's waterfront. - - - - Ports and Icepak link up to build NZ$20m hub: Ports of Auckland, Napier Port and cold storage specialist Icepak have formed a joint venture to develop a new NZ$20 million inland port and freight hub at Longburn, near Palmerston North. - - - -